04403nam a22005415i 9780520958074DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20142014cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209580747 a10.1525/97805209580742doi  a(DE-B1597)519024  a(OCoLC)868068549  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBL1278.1592.A67bL83 2014eb 7aREL0320002bisacsh04a294.50922231 aLucia, Amanda J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReflections of Amma :bDevotees in a Global Embrace /cAmanda J. Lucia. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Language -- tIntroduction. Situating Amma as Female Guru in the Context of North American Multiculturalism -- t1. A Darshan Embrace: Experiencing Authenticity and Feeling Witnessed -- t2. Devī Bhāva: Revelation and Performance of the Guru as Goddess -- t3. The Avatar- Guru and Ordinary Women: The Boundaries of Mimetic Behavioral Models -- t4. Culturally Situated Testimonies: Differing Interpretations of the Role of the Goddess -- t5. Congregational Dynamics: Growing Pains En Route from the Particular to the Universal -- tConclusion. Multiculturalism, Universalism, and Communal Identity: The Guru in the American Diaspora -- tAppendix. Current Literature Engaging the Field of Contemporary Gurus -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGlobally known as Amma, meaning "Mother," Mata Amritanandamayi has developed a massive transnational humanitarian organization based in hugs. She is familiar to millions as the "hugging saint," a moniker that derives from her elaborate darshan programs wherein nearly every day ten thousand people are embraced by the guru one at a time, events that routinely last ten to twenty hours without any rest for her. Although she was born in 1953 as a low-caste girl in a South Indian fishing village, today millions revere her as guru and goddess, a living embodiment of the divine on earth. Reflections of Amma focuses on communities of Amma's devotees in the United States, showing how they endeavor to mirror their guru's behaviors and transform themselves to emulate the ethos of the movement. This study argues that "inheritors" and "adopters" of Hindu traditions differently interpret Hindu goddesses, Amma, and her relation to feminism and women's empowerment because of their inherited religious, cultural, and political dispositions. In this insightful ethnographic analysis, Amanda J. Lucia discovers how the politics of American multiculturalism reifies these cultural differences in "de facto congregations," despite the fact that Amma's embrace attempts to erase communal boundaries in favor of global unity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aHinduismzUnited States. 7aRELIGION / Hinduism / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311062111208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520958074423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520958074.jpg  a978-3-11-062111-2  UC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-065748-7  UCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles